<ce:para>The energy optimization of bioethanol production by switchgrass gasification is presented. The process consists of three different parts. The first one is the gasification of the raw material. The second part comprises the technologies to clean up the gas from solids as well as other compounds like hydrocarbons, NH<inf>3</inf>, CO<inf>2</inf> or H<inf>2</inf>S and to adjust the gas composition. Finally, two synthetic paths are considered. The first option is the fermentation path where the synthesis gas is fermented in a stirred tank reactor. The second path for the synthesis of ethanol is the high alcohols synthesis production. The optimization of the system is formulated as a Mixed-Integer Non-linear Programming problem where all the units are modeled using short cut methods, design equations, and mass and energy balances. The problem is solved through a special decomposition scheme. An economic evaluation is performed accounting for labor, maintenance, chemicals, raw material, and utilities. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the 2010 AIChE Annual Meeting (Salt Lake City, UT 11/7-12/2010).</ce:para>
